	<div id="p256" class="post bg2">
		<div class="inner">

		<div class="postbody">
			

			<h3 class="first"><a href="#p256"></a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="./viewtopic.php?p=256#p256"><img src="./styles/modestus/imageset/icon_post_target.png" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>by <strong><a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=27">Cerbera</a></strong> &raquo; Wed May 16, 2007 8:05 pm </p>

			

			<div class="content">(I also think form validation and <span style="font-weight: bold">&lt;dialog&gt;</span> are unnecessary additions to HTML. But I assume there's a good reason for them, just that I don't know what it is.)
<br />
<br />I think anyone would agree that, on the surface, <span style="font-weight: bold">&lt;di&gt;</span> is a good idea. But since the relationship is just as unambiguous without this element, it doesn't seem to add that much value. Also, we aren't talking about deprecating <span style="font-weight: bold">&lt;di&gt;</span> and replacing it with an all-new association method, we are talking about whether <span style="font-weight: bold">&lt;di&gt;</span> is worth adding.
<br />
<br />If you are proposing that <span style="font-weight: bold">&lt;di&gt;</span> would replace the existing grouping mechanism so that it used DOM relationships rather than element types, consider this:
<br /><dl class="codebox"><dt>Code: <a href="#" onclick="selectCode(this); return false;">Select all</a></dt><dd><code>&lt;dl&gt;<br /> &lt;di&gt;<br />&nbsp; &lt;dt&gt;foo&lt;/dt&gt;<br />&nbsp; &lt;dd&gt;bar&lt;/dd&gt;<br />&nbsp; &lt;dt&gt;bish&lt;/dt&gt;<br />&nbsp; &lt;dd&gt;bash&lt;/dd&gt;<br /> &lt;/di&gt;<br />&lt;/dl&gt;</code></dd></dl>Would this mean:<br /><ul><li>foo = bar</li><li>bish = bash</li></ul>Or:<br /><ul><li>foo, bish = bar, bash</li></ul>If it's the former, the historic association method is adequate. If it's the latter, what would happen when <span style="font-weight: bold">&lt;di&gt;</span> is absent:<br /><dl class="codebox"><dt>Code: <a href="#" onclick="selectCode(this); return false;">Select all</a></dt><dd><code>&lt;dl&gt;<br /> &lt;dt&gt;foo&lt;/dt&gt;<br /> &lt;dd&gt;bar&lt;/dd&gt;<br /> &lt;dt&gt;bish&lt;/dt&gt;<br /> &lt;dd&gt;bash&lt;/dd&gt;<br />&lt;/dl&gt;</code></dd></dl>And what about when some but not all groups in a <span style="font-weight: bold">&lt;dl&gt;</span> are contained by a <span style="font-weight: bold">&lt;di&gt;</span>:<br /><dl class="codebox"><dt>Code: <a href="#" onclick="selectCode(this); return false;">Select all</a></dt><dd><code>&lt;dl&gt;<br /> &lt;di&gt;<br />&nbsp; &lt;dt&gt;foo&lt;/dt&gt;<br />&nbsp; &lt;dd&gt;bar&lt;/dd&gt;<br /> &lt;/di&gt;<br /> &lt;dt&gt;bish&lt;/dt&gt;<br /> &lt;dd&gt;bash&lt;/dd&gt;<br /> &lt;dt&gt;alpha&lt;/dt&gt;<br /> &lt;dd&gt;beta&lt;/dt&gt;<br />&lt;/dl&gt;</code></dd></dl>I think this DOM-based method would not be backwards compatible, particularly with assistive technologies. That would make HTML5's <span style="font-weight: bold">&lt;dl&gt;</span> less accessible than HTML4's -- a very undesirable outcome.
<br />
<br />It's all about the nuts and bolts!</div>

			
				<div class="notice">Last edited by <a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=27">Cerbera</a> on Wed May 16, 2007 8:23 pm, edited 8 times in total.
					
				</div>
			

		</div>

		
