	<div id="p319" class="post bg1">
		<div class="inner">

		<div class="postbody">
			

			<h3 ><a href="#p319"></a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="./viewtopic.php?p=319#p319"><img src="./styles/modestus/imageset/icon_post_target.png" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>by <strong><a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=114">Stevie D</a></strong> &raquo; Sun Jun 10, 2007 12:32 pm </p>

			

			<div class="content"><blockquote><div><cite>Cerbera wrote:</cite>And what about <span style="font-style: italic">&lt;fieldset&gt;</span>s then? Shall we call those deprecated as well, since adding <span style="font-style: italic">&lt;legends&gt;</span> to a form already implies the start of a new group of form fields as well in the same manner as a <span style="font-style: italic">&lt;dt&gt;</span> does within a <span style="font-style: italic">&lt;dl&gt;</span>. Even more perhaps as only one <span style="font-style: italic">&lt;legend&gt;</span> is allowed per group which is not the case for <span style="font-style: italic">&lt;dt&gt;</span>s.</div></blockquote>
<br />
<br />There is a key difference between <span style="font-style: italic">&lt;fieldset&gt;</span> and the proposed <span style="font-style: italic">&lt;di&gt;</span>. <span style="font-style: italic">&lt;dt&gt;</span> and <span style="font-style: italic">&lt;dd&gt;</span> elements are automatically and unambiguously associated with each other. A group of one or more contiguous <span style="font-style: italic">&lt;dt&gt;</span> elements are defined by a group of one or more contiguous <span style="font-style: italic">&lt;dd&gt;</span> elements. The association is terminated by either another <span style="font-style: italic">&lt;dt&gt;</span> element or the closing <span style="font-style: italic">&lt;/dl&gt;</span> tag.
<br />
<br />You don't get that with elements in a <span style="font-style: italic">&lt;form&gt;</span>. Form elements may be grouped together, as in a <span style="font-style: italic">&lt;fieldset&gt;</span>, or may be stand-alone items that are not grouped with any others. So while a <span style="font-style: italic">&lt;legend&gt;</span> element will implicitly begin a <span style="font-style: italic">&lt;fieldset&gt;</span>, and in doing so terminate a previous unclosed <span style="font-style: italic">&lt;fieldset&gt;</span>, there will often be times when you need to close a <span style="font-style: italic">&lt;fieldset&gt;</span> without beginning a new one.
<br />
<br />Consider the following form structure:
<br /><dl class="codebox"><dt>Code: <a href="#" onclick="selectCode(this); return false;">Select all</a></dt><dd><code>&lt;form&gt;<br />Name<br />&lt;fieldset&gt;&lt;legend&gt;Address&lt;/legend&gt;<br />Address 1<br />Address 2<br />Town<br />Postcode<br />Country<br />&lt;/fieldset&gt;<br />Age<br />&lt;/form&gt;</code></dd></dl>
<br />
<br />If you're not allowed <span style="font-style: italic">&lt;fieldset&gt;</span> elements, you can't separate off the &quot;age&quot; field at the end from the preceding &quot;address&quot; fields, other than by inserting a (completely unnecessary) <span style="font-style: italic">legend</span>.</div>

			

		</div>

		
			<dl class="postprofile" id="profile319">
			<dt>
				<a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=114">Stevie D</a>
			</dt>

